            <mi>n</mi>
            <mo>−<!-- − --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \alpha _{n-1}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/5f85641272e8866cc3ee35f7b14af4896a109612" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.671ex; width:4.807ex; height:2.009ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \alpha _{n-1}}"></span>, and hence one should allow to increase learning rate (and not just decrease as in the section Algorithm). Here is the detailed algorithm for Two-way Backtracking: At step n
</p>
<ol><li>Set <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle \gamma _{0}=\alpha _{n-1}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <msub>
          <mi>γ<!-- γ --></mi>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>α<!-- α --></mi>
          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
            <mo>−<!-- − --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
